org.apache.juddi.validation.vsv

Interface ValueSetValidator

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractSimpleValidator, Uddiuddiorgcategorizationderivedfrom, Uddiuddiorgcategorizationentitykeyvalues, Uddiuddiorgcategorizationnodes, Uddiuddiorgcategorizationowningbusiness, Uddiuddiorgcategorizationtypes, Uddiuddiorgcategorizationvalidatedby, Uddiuddiorgidentifierisreplacedby, Uddiuddiorgrelationships, Uuid25b22e3e3dfa3024b02a3438b9050b59, Uuid327a56f032994461bc235cd513e95c55, Uuid4064c0646d144f3589539652106476a9, Uuid5678dd4ff95d35f99ea6f79a7dd64656, Uuid807a2c6aee22470dadc7e0424a337c03, Uuid916b87bf075639198eae97dfa325e5a4, Uuidc1acf26d967244049d7039b756e62ab4, Uuide59ae32077a511d5b8980004ac49cc1e

    public interface ValueSetValidator
    This is the value set validator interface. It enables you to define your own validation rules for tModel Keyed References. To use this, define a tModel containing the following 
    <categoryBag>
 <keyedReference keyName=""
 keyValue="uddi:juddi.apache.org:servicebindings-valueset-cp"
 tModelKey="uddi:uddi.org:identifier:validatedby"/>
 </categoryBag>
    Where uddi:juddi.apache.org:servicebindings-valueset-cp is the binding key of the service implementing the VSV API (this service).

    From there, you need to create a class that either implements ValueSetValidator or extends AbstractSimpleValidator. It must be in the package named org.apache.juddi.validation.vsv and must by named following the convention outlined in {@link #ConvertKeyToClass(java.lang.String)
    Since:
    3.2.1
    Author:
    Alex O'Ree
    See Also:
    AbstractSimpleValidator, UDDIValueSetValidationImpl, UDDIValueSetCachingImpl
